whoami - To display the name of the user that has loogged in
apt list --installed package-name --> to check if the particular package is installed (ubuntu, debian)
cd ~ --> changes directory to home directory of the particular user
pwd -> displays present working directory
ls -> displays all available contents in the current directory
cd <directory_name> --> changes directory
cd / -> changes to root directory
cd <directory_path> -> changes to directory in the path
cd .. -> changes directory back in one step in path
clear -> clears the screen
mkdir <dirctory name> -> creates directory
rmdir <directory name> -> removes directory
sudo apt update / sudo apt-get update -> to display all the missing patches needed to be installed
sudo apt upgrade / sudo apt-get upgrade -> to install all the missing patches
nano <file name> --> used to open nano editor (used to edit the file)(Ctrl+O to save and Ctrl+x to exit the editor)
sudo apt install <package_name> --> to install particular package
vim <file_name> --> used to open vim editor (used to edit the file)(esc and :wq to save the file esc and i to edit the file)
cat <file name> --> used to display the contents of the file
ps -ef --> used to view all the running process on the device with full format (-e all process on the system) (-f full format)
touch <file_name> --> used to create a file
cat <file_name> --> used to display the contents in the file
cp <file_name> <new_file_name> --> copies the file and creates a new file
rm -f <file_name> --> rm removes the file -f removes without asking
rm -rf * -> Deletes every thing in the directory
mv <file_name> <new_path/new_file_name> --> moves to specified path and renames the file with new name
who -b --> shows last boot time
| grep -i --> -i for case insentivity
find -type d -name "<Directory_Name>" -> to view th path of specific directory
ueradd -> creating user
groupadd -> creating group
usermod -aG <group_name> <user_name> -> adds user to existing group
usermod -G <group_name> <user_name> -> adds user to existing group but deletes from other groups
passwd -S <user_name> -> check whether the account is locked L -> locked P -> active NP -> no password set
ifconfig - to show the network configurations
